    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_0",
      "value": "This tool calculates the impact of brokerage fees, loads and fund operating expenses on a mutual fund's investment returns. Returns are shown before and after taxes. All of these expenses, as well as taxes, drag down a fund's investment return."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_1",
      "value": "You pay brokerage fees when you buy and sell shares of a mutual fund. A front-end load is paid when you buy the shares. A back-end load (also called a deferred sales charge ) is paid when you redeem shares. Funds typically levy one or the other but not both. A no-load mutual fund does not charge either a front-end or a back-end load."
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf_help_2",
      "value": "Fund operating expenses include 12(b)-1 fees and are paid annually from the assets of the mutual fund. Operating expenses for many mutual funds typically range from 1.00 to 1.75 percent of fund assets each year. This ratio is called a fund's operating expense ratio."
    }
  },
